105 million PLN for video gaming companies from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost 105 million PLN of funding will go to companies in the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
On Friday, the National Centre for Research and Development announced the results of the 3rd edition of GameINN.
Almost 30 projects supported by the NCBR included, among others, the development of a platform for the development of field games based on the AR engine that creates a real world map, together with an application that enables user data to be transmitted; a test-training platform to verify practical skills at the workplace and professional improvement using VR and AI technologies; an innovative game that simulates the management of real production processes using an innovative gameplay model based on the interaction of the virtual world with the real world using the concept of Industry 4.0 – is provided in the NCBR communication sent on Friday PAP.
The objective of the GameINN sector programme is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video game industry in the global market by 2023.
According to the NCBR, already today the Polish video game sector is growing at a rate of 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion and the forecast for 2019 was PLN 2.23 billion.
"The specially prepared research agenda for GameINN and already 300 million PLN of support for entrepreneurs under this sector programme provide an important impetus for the further dynamic growth of the Polish gamedev," says the Communication.
The video gaming industry is an excellent example of the efficient use of the potential we have in Poland.
"The government's incentives for entrepreneurs to innovate, such as R & D relief, skills improvement programmes, IP boxing and support programmes implemented by the NCBR drive innovative companies and allow them to compete more effectively on a very competitive market," reports the Deputy Prime Minister, Minister for Science and Higher Education, Jarosław Gowin, quoted in the Communication.
The Head of the Ministry of Science points out that innovation money not only goes to innovators in the form of project funding, but also stays in their pockets – three quarters more entrepreneurs have benefited from R & D relief in 2018 than a year before.
"The amount of R & D costs deducted was PLN 1.7 billion, which resulted in over PLN 300 million savings for the companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in the three editions of GameINN", stresses the Deputy Prime Minister.
Director of the NCBR Dr. Wojciech Kameniecki recalls that in the two previous grant competitions with a total value of over PLN 211.2 million, 78 innovative projects were awarded.
The great interest of the third competition and the diversity of applications show that the video gaming industry has ideas and competences to further develop and enhance its competitive advantages.
"In particular, the fact that projects selected – as in previous editions – include projects on not only entertainment but also industry-related solutions 4.0" adds.
In the third GameINN competition, entrepreneurs, a consortium of entrepreneurs and a consortium of entrepreneurs with scientific entities could apply for funding of up to PLN 20 million.
The NCBR received 87 applications for a total amount of funding of approximately PLN 317 million.
The budget of the competition was PLN 100 million at the time the competition was announced, but it was increased and 27 projects were awarded almost PLN 105 million.
For more information on the results of the III GameINN competition, see ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN sectoral programme is implemented under the Intelligent Development Operational Programme.
The NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated in the Polish Games Agreement, which includes, among others, companies such as CD Project, Techland, CI Games, Bloomer Team or 11 bit studios.
