According to Iranian President Hasan Rowhani, the Americans have proposed to abolish all the sanctions imposed on Tehran in exchange for negotiating a new international agreement.
It would regulate both Iran's nuclear programme and the ballistic missile programme.
Rowhani: Iran will not make talks in the atmosphere of maximum pressure
The President of Iran said that he refused to take these talks because of the “toxic atmosphere”.
He declared that he had met with American diplomats because he had been dubbed by France, Germany and the United Kingdom.
However, he stressed that Iran would not enter into talks in the atmosphere of "maximum pressure".
"Even if we want to negotiate with the Americans in 5+1 format, no one is able to predict what the final result will be," Rowhani said.
The day before, Iran’s leader said that he did not exclude talks with the US, and the European parties to the nuclear agreement were accused of favouring US sanctions against Iran.
He added that the sanctions imposed on Iran after the US came out of the nuclear agreement “are a prerequisite that does not allow” to enter into a dialogue.
If we manage to abolish this precondition and if America endures sanctions and maximum pressure, then, of course, we can talk to America – he declared.
He added that he did not exclude a meeting with President Donald Trump, even though he did not agree to such a conversation during the UN General Assembly in the past week.
Trump: "Iran asked, I said no"
Donald Trump wrote on Twitter that he was the one who rejected the Iranian party's request.
“Iran wanted me to endure the sanctions imposed on them so that we could meet.
Of course I said "no!" tweeted the President of the United States.
A voltage with an atomic background agreement
France, Germany and the United Kingdom are trying to mitigate the tensions between Washington and Tehran in some form to save the 2015 agreement with Iran, which they were signatories to.
It stated that in exchange for the abolition of economic sanctions, Iran would abandon its nuclear weapons-building programme and that the nuclear sector would be under the control of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA).
Since the withdrawal of the agreement in May 2015, its signatories have often confirmed that they wish to maintain the agreement.
So far, none of this has worked out.
Washington is applying a tactic of putting maximum pressure on Iran, and the sanctions include a full embargo on Iranian oil.
