GUS: Poland is getting better
The report on household budgets published by the GUS on Friday shows that as a good or rather good material situation 44% of them assessed their situation.
The previous year was 37.2%, in 2016 33.5%, and earlier since 2009, when the statistical office first examined the subjective assessment of the situation of households, it never exceeded 30%.
A total of 8.1% of households considered their material situation bad or rather bad, compared to 11.2% a year before and over 20% in 2009.
The best material situation for self-employed households is the situation.
In this group, more than 70% of respondents consider it good or rather good.
At the second pole there are households rencists, where the percentage of such responses was only 18%.
The number of children also has a significant impact on the subjective assessment of the physical situation of households.
The worst is for single parents, of whom 32% declare good or rather good material situation.
The percentage of couples with children varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60%, with 48.8% of childless households.
These statistics clearly show the effect of the 500+ programme.
Before it was launched (in 2016), the worst material situation was assessed by single parents and multi-child families (with at least three children).
The improvement of subjective assessments of the situation of Poles reflects the rapid growth of income, mainly from work.
However, that is not all, because the share of households that consider their situation to be good is increasing faster than real income.
Moreover, at the level of the voivodship there is no clear link between the level of income and the assessment of the material conditions of households.
The best ratings are formulated by residents of the Opole region, where 48.9% of the surveyed consider their situation to be good or rather good.
The Lubuskie voivodeships (47.7%), Śląskie (47.6%), Mazowieckie (47.3%) and Zachodniopomorskie voivodships (47.1%) are still present.
In Opole, however, the distributional income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) was less than 94% of the national average and 98% in Lubusek.
The highest income was for Mazowiecki people (120% of the national average) and for Silesian people (104%).
On average in Poland, income per person was PLN 1693 in 2018.
In real terms (after the price adjustment), it increased by 4.3% compared to 2017.
Against the background of previous years, this is quite low.
In 2016, income per person increased by 7% and a year later by 6.3%.
Although income growth slows down, it also inhibits expenditure growth.
These per person amounted to PLN 1187, which means that they decreased by 0.7% in real terms.
This is the first case since 2013.
In 2017, expenditure per person increased by 1.9% and in 2016 by 4.3%.
Household budget surveys suggest that the statistical household currently spends 70.1% of its disposable income, while in 2014 this share was still above 80%, and by 2006 it was above 90%.
