Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for your review
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion – such an extraordinary offer prepared for the German visitors Görlitz.
Action is intended to help fight the growing decline in the population of the city.
Görlitz is the eastmost city of Germany.
A beautiful pastel old town attracts 140,000 tourists a year.
However, according to The Guardian, the city is facing considerable problems.
Görlitz has the lowest wages in Germany.
The city also faces a steady decline in the population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left to the west of the country, which translated into a 25% drop in the city's population.
In 2013, it amounted to 54 000 people.
To combat the depopulation, the officials came up with an idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
In the meantime, 150 applications have been submitted to the programme.
Two thirds of them were made up by the inhabitants of big cities.
People from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom were also interested in the program.
"When we applied, we thought the program would convince people to move to Görlitz", said one of the project participants.
"Now we feel that it doesn't matter whether we stay here after four weeks or not," he added.
The city has seven thousand free homes, and unemployment is three times higher than the average in the whole country.
Although the city authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main objective of the programme is to obtain the views of programme participants.
The information collected from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
"We want to know more about what people need and if they decide to move – what their motivation was", said Robert Knippschild.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas of attracting new residents, offering them housing incentives.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a program to pay promising young professionals for life and work in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela in Italy or in the U.S. state of Oklahoma.
